STAT-S632

Experimental Design

Two factors with no replication

The model is:

\[y_{ij} = \mu + \alpha_i + \beta_j + (\alpha \beta)_{ij} + \epsilon_{ij}\]

where \(i = 1, ..., I\) and \(j = 1, ..., J\)

\(\alpha\) is the effect of the first factor at level \(i\) and \(\beta\) is the effect of the second factor at level \(j\).

R example:

# library(faraway)
library(ggplot2)
library(car)

theme_set(theme_bw())

data(composite, package = 'faraway')

  geom_line(aes(x = laser, y = strength, group = tape, colour = tape))

ggplot(composite) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = tape, y = strength, group = laser, colour = laser))

lmod <- lm(strength ~ laser + tape + laser:tape, data = composite)

Randomized block design

Given …

  • one treatment factor \(\tau\) with \(t\) levels
  • one blocking factor \(\beta\) with \(r\) levels
  • one observation on each treatment in each block
  • limited ability to determine interactions between treatment and group (e.g., not enough observations)

The model is:

\[y_{ij} = \mu + \tau_i + \beta_j + \epsilon_{ij}\]

where \(i = 1, ..., t\) and \(j = 1, ..., r\)

\(\mu\) is the overall mean, \(\tau_i\) is the treatment effect, and \(\beta\) is the blocking effect

Can check for treatment effects and blocking effects (but not interactions)

Blocking effects are a feature of experimental units—cannot regain degrees of freedom if blocking is not significant

Comparison between complete randomized design (CRD) and randomized complete block design (RCBD):

Because block is significant, a model with blocking would be preferred

Can also consider efficiency

\(\hat{\sigma}^2_{CRD}\) vs \(\hat{\sigma}^2_{CRBD}\)

lmcrd <- lm(yield ~ variety, data = oatvar)
anova(lmcrd, lmod)

\(\sim 66\%\) more observations are needed in CRD to get the same level of precision compared to CRBD

Latin squares

Type of fractional factorial design for two blocking variables

Example: Compare 4 materials (which are our treatments): A, B, C, D, block 1: 4 positions 1, 2, 3, 4, block 2: 4 runs 1, 2, 3, 4, response: wear (weight of material worn)

data(abrasion, package = 'faraway')
summary(abrasion)
 run   position material      wear      
 1:4   1:4      A:4      Min.   :195.0  
 2:4   2:4      B:4      1st Qu.:226.8  
 3:4   3:4      C:4      Median :234.5  
 4:4   4:4      D:4      Mean   :239.5  
                         3rd Qu.:255.2  
                         Max.   :274.0

[1,] "C"  "D"  "B"  "A" 
[2,] "A"  "B"  "D"  "C" 
[3,] "D"  "C"  "A"  "B" 
[4,] "B"  "A"  "C"  "D"

Note that each treatment is assigned to each block only once

The model:

\[y_{ijk} = \mu + \tau_i + \beta_j + \gamma_k + \epsilon_{ijk}\]

\(i, j, k\) all have same number of levels \(1, ..., t\), but not all appear in the data

  • Latin square can be more efficient than RCBD
  • block sizes (levels) should be equal to treatments (levels)
  • can be used to compare three treatment factors
  • cannot estimate interactions
ggplot(abrasion) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = run, y = wear, colour = position, group = material))

ggplot(abrasion) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = position, y = wear, colour = run, group = material))

lmod <- lm(wear ~ material + run + position, data = abrasion)
summary(lmod)
